        The Interest Rate Cycle and Timing Your Brisbane Property Sale: When to Wait, When to Act
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The RBA cash rate moves buyer borrowing capacity and sentiment, but trying to time the cycle perfectly is a losing strategy for most sellers. Here's a practical framework.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The RBA cash rate gets more attention in property conversations than almost any other variable, and there is a real reason for that: rate movements affect buyer borrowing capacity and sentiment, and can shift overall buyer demand by something in the order of 5 to 15% in either direction. That is meaningful. The mistake most sellers make is assuming this means they should be timing the cycle, holding off in rising-rate periods and rushing to sell at the bottom. Trying to time the cycle perfectly is a losing strategy for most sellers, and in many cases it produces a worse outcome than simply transacting when personal circumstances call for it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The four phases of the rate cycle</h2>
      <p>Australian rate cycles have characteristic phases, and each one carries a recognisable signal for the property market. In rising-rate periods, buyer borrowing capacity declines as the maximum loan amount lenders will approve falls, and sentiment becomes cautious. At peak rates, uncertainty dominates. Buyers wait for direction, transaction volumes drop, and clearance rates compress. In falling-rate periods, borrowing capacity expands again and sentiment improves visibly: buyers come back to open homes, finance approvals come through, and competition begins to return. In sustained low-rate periods, buyer competition is strong, sentiment is positive, and auction clearance rates rise.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What each phase means for sellers</h2>
      <p>For sellers, the practical translation is this. Rising rates: campaigns slow, the buyer pool narrows, prices may flatten or soften. Peak rates: buyers wait for clarity, transaction volumes are low, deals are scarcer and harder. Falling rates: confidence returns, prices typically firm, finance approvals come through more readily. Low rates: auction clearance rates rise, multiple-offer scenarios become more common, results sit at the upper end of evidence. The pattern is real, but it is the average across many properties. Your specific outcome depends on much more than the cycle phase.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The timing question: wait for cuts</h2>
      <p>If rates are at or near peak and the data suggests cuts are likely in the next few months, waiting 3 to 6 months can produce a stronger sale. The market typically moves before the cuts arrive: buyers anticipate the change and move back into the market once the direction looks clear. But this is a conditional statement, not a rule. The decision to wait depends on the seller's circumstances first and the market conditions second, never the other way around.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The timing question: sell at peak</h2>
      <p>The counter-argument is often missed. Selling during high-rate periods may achieve a lower price than selling six months later. But the seller can also buy at lower prices in the same market. For upgraders, downsizers, or anyone moving within the same regional market, the relative position is what matters: the gap between the sale price and the purchase price, not the absolute level of either one. A seller who waits 12 months for rates to fall before selling will often find that the property they were planning to buy has appreciated by more than their own home. The headline gain disappears.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The personal circumstances test</h2>
      <p>Before any market timing logic applies, the personal circumstances test should be answered first. Is the move time-sensitive: a job change, a family reason, a health consideration? What is the cost of waiting in carrying costs, bridging finance, lifestyle disruption, or simply ongoing maintenance and rates? Is the property's condition deteriorating without active intervention? If any of those answers points toward acting now, the rate cycle becomes a secondary consideration at best.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What genuine market data tells you</h2>
      <p>The data points that actually inform timing decisions are local and specific. Auction clearance rates above 65% indicate a strong buyer market regardless of rate level. Median days on market under 30 indicate a competitive market. RBA forward-looking statements about rate direction give some signal about the next few months. Buyer finance approval data from major banks gives an early read on whether borrowing capacity is firming or weakening. These are useful inputs. None of them is a market-timing oracle.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ignore</h2>
      <p>The least useful inputs to a timing decision are the loudest. Media headlines forecasting market crashes or booms are reliably wrong at turning points. Single-month price movements are volatile and noisy and rarely predict the next month. Predictions from sources without economic credentials should be treated as entertainment, not analysis. The honest reality is that even professional economists get rate-cycle calls wrong regularly. Building your sale strategy around someone else's forecast is building it on sand.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The upgrader's specific math</h2>
      <p>If you are selling and buying in the same market, rate effects largely cancel out. Your home will sell for less in a soft market, but the home you buy will also cost less. Your primary concern is the relative gap between the two transactions, and that gap is often more favourable in slower markets when buyers are scarce and you have negotiating leverage on the purchase side. Many upgraders who waited for 'better conditions' did worse than upgraders who acted in the slow market they were in.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The investor's specific math</h2>
      <p>For investors selling, the calculation is different. Rates affect both the selling price and the buyer's investment yield calculation. High rates compress buyer yields and may discount the property below the level a confident buyer would pay in lower-rate conditions. Investors with flexibility on timing can often gain by selling into improving rather than peak-rate markets. But the personal circumstances test still applies, and the holding cost of waiting must be priced in.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The downsizer's specific math</h2>
      <p>Downsizers are in a different position again. They are typically locking in capital gains and care more about the absolute sale price than the relative gap, because the purchase side is often a smaller, lower-cost property. For them, selling near peak prices may matter more than for upgraders. But the cost of waiting must include carrying costs of the larger home, ongoing maintenance, and the lifestyle reasons that prompted the downsizing decision in the first place.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do</h2>
      <p>Do not delay selling indefinitely waiting for the perfect cycle phase. The perfect phase is only visible in hindsight. Do not assume that rate cuts always produce immediate price rises: they often produce a confidence shift before any price move. Do not let speculative forecasts override personal financial planning. The cost of getting timing wrong is high in both directions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Personal circumstances drive timing more than rate cycles for most sellers. If your move is needed within 12 months, plan to sell within 12 months. Trying to time within that window has low expected value and often produces a worse result than committing to a campaign and executing it well. If your move is genuinely flexible, selling into a recovering market (post-rate-cut) typically beats selling into rising rates, but the difference is smaller than headlines suggest, and preparation and execution will move your result more than the month you choose to list.</p>

